	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	starting February&nbsp;1, 2018. Early adoption to the original public company adoption timelines is permitted. The Company has not yet selected a transition method and is currently in the process
	of determining the impact on its consolidated financial statements and related disclosures.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3. Fair Value Measurements
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Fair value is defined as the exchange price that would be received for an asset or paid to transfer a liability (an exit price) in the principal or most
	advantageous market for the asset or liability in an orderly transaction between market participants on the measurement date. Valuation techniques used to measure fair value must maximize the use of observable inputs and minimize the use of
	unobservable inputs. The standard describes a fair value hierarchy based on three levels of inputs, of which the first two are considered observable and the last unobservable, to measure the fair value:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:4PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Level 1&#151;Inputs are unadjusted quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:4PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Level 2&#151;Inputs are quoted prices for similar assets and liabilities in active markets or inputs other than quoted prices that are observable for the assets or liabilities, either directly or indirectly through
	market corroboration, for substantially the full term of the financial instruments.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:4PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Level 3&#151;Inputs are unobservable inputs based on the Company&#146;s own assumptions used to measure assets and liabilities at fair value. The inputs require significant management judgment or estimation.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Beginning November 2014, the Company entered into foreign currency forward contracts to minimize the short-term impact of foreign
	currency exchange rate fluctuations on cash and certain trade and inter-company receivables and payables. These are not designated hedge instruments. These instruments are marked to market through earnings every period and generally have an original
	maturity period of one month. These instruments are classified within level 2 of the fair value hierarchy. The Company&#146;s derivative assets and derivative liabilities as of January&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015 are as follows (in thousands):
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Depreciation expense related to property and equipment for the years ended January&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014 was
	$15.6 million, $8.8 million and $4.2 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5. Employee Loans
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	During the years ended January&nbsp;31, 2011 and 2012, the Company issued full recourse loans to two employees to facilitate the exercise of their stock
	options. The first of these loans was issued in December 2011 with a principal amount of $1.0 million and an interest rate of at 1.3%&nbsp;per annum. The loan was contractually due and payable in full in December 2020 or upon such earlier date that
	the Company files a registration statement related to an initial public offering. The second of these loans was issued in June 2012 with a principal amount of $0.4 million and an interest of 2.3%&nbsp;per annum. The loan was contractually due and
	payable in full in June 2020 or upon such earlier date that the Company files a registration statement related to an initial public offering. The principal loan amount and the accrued interest were $1.6 million as of January&nbsp;31, 2013, and were
	reported as a deduction from stockholders&#146; equity (deficit) on the Company&#146;s consolidated statements of redeemable convertible preferred stock and stockholders&#146; equity (deficit). Both of these loans and related interest were repaid in
	full in August 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	6. Commitments and Contingencies
</B>
</P>

<B>
<I>
	Leases

</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company leases its facilities under various noncancelable operating leases with fixed rental payments. Rent expense totaled $6.2
	million, $5.3 million and $3.1 million for the years ended January&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively. Future minimum commitments under these operating leases as of January&nbsp;31, 2016 were as follows (in thousands):

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	In July 2014, the Company entered into a facility lease agreement for its North Carolina office. The
	84-month lease commenced on August&nbsp;1, 2014. Total rent, including common area maintenance expense and fixed operating expense, payable over the lease period is $5.0 million. As part of the lease agreement, the Company received $1.4 million in
	tenant improvements allowance during the year ended January&nbsp;31, 2016. This allowance was included in the calculation of rent expense and related deferred rent balances. In December 2014, the Company amended the lease agreement for its North
	Carolina office giving the Company access to an additional space on February&nbsp;1, 2016 through the same term as the original facility lease. As part of the lease amendment, the Company will receive an allowance of $1.0 million for tenant
	improvements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	In April 2013, the Company entered into a facility lease agreement for its headquarters in San Jose, California. The 96-month lease
	commenced on November&nbsp;1, 2013. Total rent, including operating expenses, payable over the lease period is $35.5 million. As part of the lease agreement, the Company received $4.9 million in tenant improvement allowance during the year ended
	January&nbsp;31, 2014. This allowance was included in the calculation of rent expense and related deferred rent balances. As a condition of the lease agreement, the Company is required to maintain a letter of credit of $3.9 million, with the
	landlord named as the beneficiary. The Company has the option to extend the term of the lease for an additional period of 60 months.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
<I>
	Contingencies
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	From time to time, the Company is party to litigation and subject to claims that arise in the ordinary course of business, including actions
	with respect to employment claims and other matters. Although the results of litigation and claims are inherently unpredictable, the Company believes that the final outcome of such matters will not have a material adverse effect on the business,
	consolidated financial position, results of operations or cash flows.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	On December&nbsp;17, 2015, a purported securities class action entitled
	Vikramkumar v. Nimble Storage, Inc., et al. was filed in the United States District Court for the Northern District of California, against the Company and certain of its officers and directors. A second purported securities class action entitled
	Guardino v. Nimble Storage, Inc., et al. was filed on December&nbsp;23, 2015, and a third purported class action entitled Madhani v. Nimble Storage, Inc., et al. was filed on February&nbsp;5, 2016, also in the Northern District of California against
	the same parties. The complaints in the three actions allege claims under Sections 10(b) and 20(a) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended, based on allegedly misleading statements regarding the Company&#146;s business and financial
	results. On March&nbsp;28, 2016, the Court ordered that the three actions be consolidated under the caption
<I>
	In re Nimble Storage, Inc. Securities Litigation
</I>
	. The Company has not yet responded to any complaint. Given the early stage in the
	litigation, we are unable to estimate a possible loss or range of possible loss.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	On February&nbsp;23, 2016, a purported shareholder derivative
	action entitled Schwartz v. Vasudevan, et al. was filed in the United States District Court for the Northern District of California, against certain of the Company&#146;s officers and directors. The complaint alleges that defendants breached their
	fiduciary duties by allowing the Company to make allegedly misleading statements regarding the Company&#146;s business and financial results, and by selling stock while in possession of material non-public information. Given the early stage in the
	litigation, we are unable to estimate a possible loss or range of possible loss.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
<I>
	Indemnification
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Some of the Company&#146;s sales contracts require the Company to indemnify its end-customers against third-party claims asserting infringement of
	certain intellectual property rights, which may include patents, copyrights, trademarks, or trade secrets, and to pay judgments entered on such
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="CENTER">
	81
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage84"></A>

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D139469D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	claims. The Company&#146;s exposure under these indemnification provisions is generally limited to the total amount paid by the end-customer under the contract. However, certain contracts include
	indemnification provisions that could potentially expose the Company to losses in excess of the amount received under the contract. In addition, the Company indemnifies its officers, directors, and certain key employees while they are serving in
	good faith in their respective capacities. To date, there have been no claims under any indemnification provisions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
<I>
	Purchase Commitments
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company purchases components from a variety of suppliers and one contract manufacturer to provide manufacturing services for products. During the
	normal course of business, in order to manage manufacturing lead times and help ensure adequate component supply, the Company enters into agreements with its contract manufacturer and suppliers that either allow them to procure inventory based upon
	criteria as defined by the Company or that establish the parameters defining the requirements. These agreements generally do not include any legally binding minimum commitment obligations. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, the Company had $36.4 million
	in several operating commitments to fulfill inventory requirements arising from growing forecasts and several non-cancelable software license and service agreements for the internal use of software and services for vendor and customer relationship
	management, human resource, inventory forecasting application and communication and desktop applications.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	7. Common Stock
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	In December 2013, the Company completed its initial public offering of 9.2&nbsp;million shares of its common stock at a public offering price of $21.00
	per share. Net cash proceeds from the initial public offering were approximately $175.4 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	In connection with the closing of the initial
	public offering, all of the shares of preferred stock outstanding automatically converted into an aggregate of 38.9&nbsp;million shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	On December&nbsp;18, 2013, the Company filed its Restated Certificate of Incorporation in connection with the closing of its initial public offering.
	Following the amendment, the Company had authorized capital stock of 755.0&nbsp;million shares, comprising: (i)&nbsp;750.0&nbsp;million shares of common stock, par value $0.001 per share and (ii)&nbsp;5.0&nbsp;million shares of preferred stock, par
	value $0.001 per share.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, there were 750.0&nbsp;million shares of common stock authorized with a par value of $0.001 per
	share. The Company had reserved the following shares of authorized but unissued common stock (in thousands):

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	8. Equity Incentive Plans
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
<I>
	Plan
	Descriptions
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<I>
	2008 Equity Incentive Plan
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	In May 2008, the Company adopted the 2008 Equity Incentive Plan, or the 2008 Plan, for the benefit of its eligible employees, consultants, and
	independent directors. The 2008 Plan provides for
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="CENTER">
	82
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage85"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D139469D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	the grant of stock awards, including incentive stock options, nonqualified stock options, restricted stock, stock appreciation rights and RSUs. The Company grants stock options with an exercise
	price equal to the fair market value of its common stock on the date of the grant, as determined by the board of directors. The Company&#146;s equity awards vest over a period of time as determined by the board of directors and expire no later than
	10 years from the date of grant. Grants to new employees generally vest over a four-year period, at a rate of 25% one year from the date the optionee&#146;s service period begins and 1/48 monthly thereafter. Subject to adjustment for certain changes
	in the Company&#146;s capital structure, the maximum aggregate number of shares of common stock that may be issued under the 2008 Plan is 55.6 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	In December 2013, in connection with the closing of the Company&#146;s initial public offering, the 2008 Plan was terminated and shares authorized for
	issuance under the 2008 Plan were cancelled (except for those shares reserved for issuance upon exercise of outstanding stock options). As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, options to purchase and RSUs to convert to a total of 8.8&nbsp;million shares of
	common stock were outstanding under the 2008 Plan pursuant to their original terms and no shares were available for future grant.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<I>
	2013 Equity
	Incentive Plan
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	In September 2013, the Company adopted the 2013 Equity Incentive Plan, or the 2013 Plan, which became effective on
	December&nbsp;12, 2013 and serves as the successor to the Company&#146;s 2008 Plan. Upon completion of the Company&#146;s initial public offering, the Company ceased granting awards under the 2008 Plan and any remaining shares available for issuance
	under the 2008 Plan were added to the shares reserved under the 2013 Plan. The 2013 Plan will terminate in September 2023, unless sooner terminated by the board of directors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The 2013 Plan provides for the grant of incentive stock options, non-statutory stock options, restricted stock awards, stock bonus awards, stock
	appreciation rights, RSUs and performance awards, all of which may be granted to eligible employees, consultants or directors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Under the terms of
	the 2013 Plan, awards may be granted at prices not less than 100% of the fair value of the Company&#146;s common stock, as determined by the Company&#146;s board of directors, on the date of grant for stock options. Options vest over a period of
	time as determined by the board of directors, generally a four-year period, and expire ten years from date of grant.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Initially, the aggregate
	number of shares of the Company&#146;s common stock that may be issued pursuant to stock awards under the 2013 Plan after the 2013 Plan became effective was 10.2&nbsp;million shares, plus any reserved shares not issued or subject to outstanding
	grants under the 2008 Plan on the date the 2013 Plan became effective, shares that are subject to stock options or RSUs granted under the 2008 Plan that cease to be subject to such stock options or other awards by forfeiture or otherwise or are
	issued and later forfeited or repurchased by the Company after the date the 2013 Plan became effective, and shares that are subject to stock options or other awards under the 2008 Plan that are used to pay the exercise price of an option or withheld
	to satisfy the tax withholding obligations related to any award. The number of shares available for grant and issuance under the 2013 Plan will automatically increase on February&nbsp;1
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	st
</SUP>
	of each
	of the calendar years 2014 through 2022, by the lesser of (i)&nbsp;5% of the number of shares issued and outstanding on each January&nbsp;31
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	st
</SUP>
	immediately prior to the date of increase or
	(ii)&nbsp;such number of shares determined by the Company&#146;s board of directors. The maximum number of shares that may be issued pursuant to the exercise of incentive stock options under the 2013 Plan is 300.0&nbsp;million shares. As of
	January&nbsp;31, 2016, stock options to purchase and RSUs to convert to a total of 9.7&nbsp;million shares of common stock were outstanding under the 2013 Plan and 6.8&nbsp;million shares were reserved for future issuance.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<I>
	2013 Employee Stock Purchase Plan
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	In
	September 2013, the Company adopted the ESPP which became effective on December&nbsp;12, 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="CENTER">
	83
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage86"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D139469D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The ESPP initially authorizes the issuance of 2.0&nbsp;million shares of the Company&#146;s common stock
	pursuant to purchase rights granted to eligible employees. The number of shares of common stock reserved for issuance will automatically increase on February&nbsp;1
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	st
</SUP>
	of each calendar year, by an
	amount equal to (i)&nbsp;1% of the total number of outstanding shares of common stock and common stock equivalents on the immediately preceding January&nbsp;31
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	st
</SUP>
	, or (ii)&nbsp;such lesser number
	of shares of common stock as determined by the Company&#146;s board of directors. The maximum number of shares that may be issued pursuant to the ESPP is 30.0&nbsp;million shares. The ESPP is intended to qualify as an &#147;employee stock purchase
	plan&#148; within the meaning of Section&nbsp;423 of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended, or the Internal Revenue Code.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The ESPP was
	implemented through a series of offerings of purchase rights to eligible employees. Except for the initial offering period, each offering period is for 24 months beginning March&nbsp;10
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	th
</SUP>
	and
	September&nbsp;10
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	th
</SUP>
	of each year, with each such offering period consisting of four six-month purchase periods. The initial offering period began December&nbsp;12, 2013 and ended on March&nbsp;9,
	2016, with purchase dates on September&nbsp;9, 2014,&nbsp;March&nbsp;9, 2015,&nbsp;September&nbsp;9, 2015 and March&nbsp;9, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Eligible
	employees may participate through payroll deductions of 1% to 15% of their earnings. Common stock will be issued to participating employees at a price per share equal to 85% of the lesser of (i)&nbsp;the fair market value on the offering date, or
	(ii)&nbsp;the fair market value on the purchase date. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, the Company had 2.6&nbsp;million shares reserved for future issuance.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
<I>
	Early Exercises of Stock Options
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Stock options
	granted under the 2008 Plan provide employee option holders, if approved by the board of directors, the right to exercise unvested options in exchange for restricted common stock, which is subject to a repurchase right held by the Company at the
	lower of (i)&nbsp;the fair market value of its common stock on the date of repurchase or (ii)&nbsp;the original purchase price. Early exercises of options are not deemed to be substantive exercises for accounting purposes and accordingly, amounts
	received for early exercises are recorded as a liability. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, there were 0.2&nbsp;million and 0.7&nbsp;million shares, respectively, subject to repurchase related to stock options early exercised and unvested. These
	amounts are reclassified to common stock and additional paid-in capital as the underlying shares vest. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, the Company recorded a liability related to these shares subject to repurchase in the amount of $0.7 million
	and $2.1 million, respectively, within other long-term liabilities in its consolidated balance sheets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
<I>
	Fair Value of Common Stock
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Prior to the Company&#146;s initial public offering, the Company&#146;s board of directors considered numerous objective and subjective factors to
	determine the fair value of common stock at each grant date. These factors included, but were not limited to, (i)&nbsp;contemporaneous valuations of common stock performed by unrelated third-party firms; (ii)&nbsp;the prices for the preferred stock
	sold to outside investors; (iii)&nbsp;the rights, preferences and privileges of the preferred stock relative to the common stock; (iv)&nbsp;the lack of marketability of the Company&#146;s common stock; (v)&nbsp;developments in the business; and
	(vi)&nbsp;the likelihood of achieving a liquidity event, such as an initial public offering or a merger or acquisition of the Company, given prevailing market conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company has used the publicly quoted price as the fair value of its common stock since its common stock became publicly traded in December 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="CENTER">
	84
</P>

	The options exercisable as of January&nbsp;31, 2016 included options that are exercisable prior to vesting. The
	intrinsic value of options vested and expected to vest and become exercisable as of January&nbsp;31, 2016 was calculated based on the difference between the exercise price and the fair value of the Company&#146;s common stock as of January&nbsp;31,
	2016. The intrinsic value of exercised options for the years ended January&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014 was $63.1 million, $89.1 million and $10.0 million, respectively, and was calculated based on the difference between the exercise price and the
	fair value of the Company&#146;s common stock as of the exercise date.

	January&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014 was $8.4 million, $11.4 million and $3.9 million, respectively.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company did not issue any stock options in the year ended January&nbsp;31, 2016. The weighted-average fair value of
	options granted was $14.52 and $3.94 per share for the years ended January&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. The Company started to issue RSUs in the year ended January&nbsp;31, 2014. The weighted-average fair value of RSUs granted was $19.61,
	$31.30 and $18.92 per share for the years ended January&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively. The weighted average fair value of stock purchase rights granted was $7.04, $7.20 and $6.91 per share for the year ended January&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015
	and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company issues RSUs to certain employees based on the Company meeting certain performance thresholds. The estimated
	probability of the number of these RSUs expected to vest is assessed for each reporting period until the total shares granted are determined. For the year ended January&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, the Company recognized expense of $5.0 million and $7.2
	million stock-based compensation related to these RSUs, respectively. The reduction of expense related to these RSUs in the year ended January&nbsp;31, 2016 is due to a reduction in estimated achievement of performance thresholds for fiscal year
	2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, there was $9.2 million of unrecognized stock-based compensation expense for stock options that will be
	recognized over the remaining weighted-average period of 1.6 years. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, there was $183.4 million of unrecognized stock-based compensation expense for RSUs that will be recognized over the remaining weighted-average period of
	2.8 years. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, there was $1.8 million of unrecognized stock-based compensation expense for stock purchase rights that will be recognized over the remaining offering period, through September 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company accounted for the stock purchase rights under ESPP at the grant date (first day of the offering period) by valuing the four purchase periods
	separately. The option was valued using the Black-Scholes-Merton option-pricing model with the following assumptions:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<I>
	Expected Term.
</I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The expected term for the ESPP is based on the length of the offering
	period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Expected Volatility.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Since the Company does not have sufficient trading history for its common stock, the expected
	volatility used is based on volatility of similar entities. In evaluating similarity, the Company considered factors such as industry, stage of life cycle, size, and financial leverage.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

</P>

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D139469D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<I>
	Risk-Free Interest Rate
</I>
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The risk-free rate that the Company used is based on
	U.S. Treasury zero-coupon issues with remaining terms similar to the expected term of the ESPP.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<I>
	Dividend Yield
</I>
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	Company has never declared or paid any cash dividends and does not plan to pay cash dividends in the foreseeable future and, therefore, uses an expected dividend yield of zero in the valuation model.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company is required to estimate forfeitures at the time of grant and revise those estimates in subsequent periods if actual forfeitures differ from
	those estimates. The Company uses historical data to estimate pre-vesting option forfeitures and records stock-based compensation expense only for those awards that are expected to vest.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	9. 401(k) Plan
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company has a qualified defined
	contribution plan under Section&nbsp;401(k) of the Internal Revenue Code covering eligible employees. Participants may make pre-tax contributions to the plan from their eligible earnings up to the statutorily prescribed annual limit on pre-tax
	contributions under the Internal Revenue Code. Although the plan provides for a discretionary employer matching contribution, to date the Company has not made such a contribution on behalf of employees.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	10. Income Taxes
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The provision for income taxes is based
	upon the loss before provision for income taxes as follows (in thousands):

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company&#146;s provision for income taxes of $1.0 million for the year ended January&nbsp;31, 2016 consisted of
	current foreign taxes, current state taxes and deferred foreign taxes. The Company&#146;s provision for income taxes of $0.8 million for the year ended January&nbsp;31, 2015 consisted of current foreign taxes, current state taxes and deferred
	foreign taxes. The Company&#146;s provision for income taxes of $0.4 million for the year ended January&nbsp;31, 2014 consisted of current foreign taxes, current federal taxes, current state taxes and deferred foreign taxes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company&#146;s effective tax rate differs from the U.S. federal statutory tax rate due to the following (in thousands):

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The net valuation allowance increased by $38.1 million during the year ended January&nbsp;31, 2016. Management has
	recorded a full valuation allowance against its net domestic deferred tax assets as it is not more likely than not that the assets will be realized based on the Company&#146;s history of losses.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">

	R&amp;D tax credit effective January&nbsp;1, 2015. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, the Company had net operating loss, or NOL, carryforwards and research and development credits as follows (in thousands):

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company uses the &#145;with-and-without&#146; approach to determine the recognition and measurement of excess tax
	benefits. Accordingly, the Company has elected to recognize excess income tax benefits from stock option exercises in additional paid in capital only if an incremental income tax benefit would be realized after considering all other tax attributes
	presently available to the Company. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, the amount of such excess tax benefits from stock options included in NOLs was $97.3 million and $22.9 million for federal and California purposes. In addition, the Company has elected
	to account for the indirect effects of stock-based awards on other tax attributes, such as the research and alternative minimum tax credits, through its statements of operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Under Section&nbsp;382 of the Internal Revenue Code, the Company&#146;s ability to utilize NOL carryforwards or other tax attributes, such as research
	tax credits, in any taxable year may be limited if the Company experiences an &#147;ownership change.&#148; A Section&nbsp;382 &#147;ownership change&#148; generally occurs if one or more stockholders or groups of stockholders who own at least 5% of
	the Company&#146;s stock increase their ownership by more than 50 percentage points over their lowest ownership percentage within a rolling three-year period. Similar rules may apply under state tax laws. It is possible that an ownership change, or
	any future ownership change, could have a material effect on the use of the Company&#146;s NOL carryforwards or other tax attributes. Due to the existence of the valuation allowance, future changes in unrecognized tax benefits will not impact the
	Company&#146;s effective tax rate.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="CENTER">
	88
</P>

	no deferred tax liability has been established relative to these earnings. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, the Company&#146;s undistributed earnings of foreign subsidiaries were $4.6 million.

	recognized de minimis interest and penalties related to uncertain tax positions for the years ended January&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The gross unrecognized tax benefits, if recognized, would affect the effective tax rate by approximately $410,000 and
	$39,000 as of January&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, respectively. While it is often difficult to predict the final outcome of any particular uncertain tax position, the Company does not believe it is reasonably possible that the total amount of
	unrecognized tax benefits as of January&nbsp;31, 2016 will materially change in the next 12 months.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company files federal, state, and foreign
	income tax returns in many jurisdictions in the United States and abroad. For U.S. federal and state income tax purposes, the statute of limitations currently remains open for all years due to the Company&#146;s NOL carryforwards. The Company is not
	currently under examination in any jurisdiction.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	11. Segments
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The Company&#146;s chief operating decision maker is its chief executive officer. The chief executive officer reviews consolidated financial information
	accompanied by information about revenue by product line for purposes of allocating resources and evaluating financial performance. The Company has one business activity and there are no segment managers who are held accountable for operations, or
	operating results for levels or components. In addition, the majority of the Company&#146;s operations and end-customers are located in the United States. As such, the Company has a single reporting segment and a single operating unit structure.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="CENTER">
	89
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	12. Line of Credit
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	In
	October 2013, the Company entered into an agreement with Wells Fargo Bank, National Association, or Wells Fargo, to provide a secured revolving credit facility, or the Credit Facility, that allows the Company to borrow up to $15.0 million for
	general corporate purposes. There was a $0.9 million reduction of the available line related to a letter of credit issued in July 2014 for the Company&#146;s facility lease in North Carolina. In April 2015, the Company increased its letter of credit
	from $0.9 million to $1.1 million, with the landlord named as the beneficiary. In January 2016, there was a $3.9 million reduction of the available line related to a letter of credit issued for the Company&#146;s headquarters facility lease in
	California, with the landlord named as the beneficiary. As a consequence, the Company released its restricted cash of $3.9 million. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, the remaining Credit Facility available for borrowings was $10.0 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Amounts outstanding under the Credit Facility will bear interest at Wells Fargo&#146;s prime rate with accrued interest payable on a monthly basis. In
	addition, the Company is obligated to pay a commitment fee of 0.20%&nbsp;per annum on the unused portion of the Credit Facility, with such fee payable on a quarterly basis. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, the commitment fee was capitalized and being
	amortized on the Company&#146;s consolidated balance sheet. The Credit Facility was renewed in September 2014 for an incremental two-year period and now expires in October 2016. Under the Credit Facility renewal, the Company granted to Wells Fargo a
	first priority lien in its accounts receivable and other corporate assets, agreed to not pledge its intellectual property to other parties and became subject to certain reporting and financial covenants, as follows: (i)&nbsp;maintain minimum
	tangible net worth, defined as the aggregate of total stockholders&#146; equity plus subordinated debt less any intangible assets and less any loans or advances to, or investments in, any related entities or individuals, of $135 million; and
	(ii)&nbsp;maintain a monthly ratio of not less than 1.25 to 1.00, based on the aggregate of its cash and net accounts receivable divided by total current liabilities minus current deferred revenue. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, no amounts had been
	drawn against the Credit Facility and the Company was in compliance with all covenants associated with the Credit Facility.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="CENTER">
	90
</P>

<A NAME="FIS_ACCOUNTING_CHANGES"></A>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

	ITEM&nbsp;9.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	CHANGES IN AND DISAGREEMENTS WITH ACCOUNTANTS ON ACCOUNTING AND FINANCIAL DISCLOSURE
</B>
</TD>

<EFX_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES>
<A NAME="FIS_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES"></A>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="9%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
<A NAME="D139469D10K_HTM_TOC139469_13">
</A>
	ITEM&nbsp;9A.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	CONTROLS AND PROCEDURES
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Regulations under the Exchange Act, require public companies to maintain
	&#147;disclosure controls and procedures.&#148; Rule 13a-15(e) and Rule 15d-15(e) require that a company&#146;s controls and other procedures are designed to ensure information required to be disclosed in the reports it files, or submits under the
	Exchange Act, is recorded, processed, summarized and reported, within the time periods specified in the SEC&#146;s rules and forms. Disclosure controls and procedures include, without limitation, controls and other procedures designed to ensure
	information required to be disclosed by a company in the reports that it files or submits under the Exchange Act is accumulated and communicated to the company&#146;s management, including its principal executive and principal financial officers, as
	appropriate, to allow timely decisions regarding required disclosure.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Limitation of the Effectiveness of Controls
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	In designing and evaluating our disclosure controls and procedures and internal control over financial reporting, management recognizes that any controls
	and procedures, no matter how well conceived and operated, can provide only reasonable, not absolute, assurance that the objectives of the controls and procedures are met. Additionally, in designing disclosure controls and procedures and internal
	control over financial reporting, our management necessarily was required to apply its judgment in evaluating the cost-benefit relationship of possible controls and procedures.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Evaluation of Disclosure Controls and Procedures
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Our
	management, with the participation of our principal executive officer and principal financial officer, evaluated the effectiveness of our disclosure controls and procedures pursuant to Rules 13a-15(e) and 15d-15(e) under the Exchange Act, as of the
	end of the period covered by this Annual Report on Form 10-K for the financial year ended January&nbsp;31, 2016. Based on the evaluation, as of January&nbsp;31, 2016, our principal executive officer and principal financial officer concluded that our
	disclosure controls and procedures are designed at a reasonable assurance level and are effective to provide reasonable assurance that information we are required to disclose in reports that we file or submit under the Exchange Act is recorded,
	processed, summarized and reported within the time periods specified in the SEC&#146;s rules and forms, and that such information is accumulated and communicated to our management, including our principal executive officer and principal financial
	officer, as appropriate, to allow timely decisions regarding required disclosure.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Management&#146;s Annual Report on Internal Control Over Financial Reporting
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Our management is responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate internal control over financial reporting (as defined in Rule 13a-15(f)
	under the Exchange Act) to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of our financial reporting and the preparation of consolidated financial statements for external purposes in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting
	principles.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Management conducted an assessment of the effectiveness of our internal control over financial reporting based on the criteria set
	forth in Internal Control&#151;Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (2013 framework). Management&#146;s assessment included evaluation of elements such as the design and operating
	effectiveness of key financial reporting controls, process documentation, accounting policies, and our overall control environment. Based on the assessment, management has concluded that our internal control over financial reporting was effective as
	of January&nbsp;31, 2016 to provide reasonable assurance
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="CENTER">
	92
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage95"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D139469D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements in accordance with U.S. GAAP. We reviewed the results of management&#146;s assessment with the Audit
	Committee of our board of directors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Our independent registered public accounting firm, Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP, independently assessed the
	effectiveness of the company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting, as stated in the firm&#146;s attestation report, which is included within Part II, Item&nbsp;8 of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Changes in Internal Control over Financial Reporting
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	There
	were no changes in our internal control over financial reporting identified in management&#146;s evaluation pursuant to Rules 13a-15(d) or 15d-15(d) of the Exchange Act during the quarter ended January&nbsp;31, 2016 that materially affected, or are
	reasonably likely to materially affect, our internal control over financial reporting.
</P>
</EFX_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES>

<EFX_DIRECTORS_AND_OFFICERS>
<A NAME="FIS_DIRECTORS_AND_OFFICERS"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	I
<A NAME="D139469D10K_HTM_TOC139469_15">
</A>
	TEM&nbsp;10. DIRECTORS, EXECUTIVE OFFICERS AND CORPORATE GOVERNANCE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	The information required by this item is incorporated herein by
	reference to information contained in the Proxy Statement for our 2016 Annual Meeting of Stockholders.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Section&nbsp;16(a) Beneficial Ownership Reporting
	Compliance
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Exchange Act requires our directors, executive officers and any persons who own more than 10% of the
	Company&#146;s common stock (collectively &#147;reporting persons&#148;), to file initial reports of ownership and reports of changes in ownership with the SEC. Such persons are required by SEC regulation to furnish us with copies of all
	Section&nbsp;16(a) forms that they file.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Codes of Business Conduct and Ethics
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
	We have adopted codes of ethics, our Code of Business Conduct and Ethics for employees, which applies to all employees, including our principal executive
	officers, our principal financial officer and all other executive officers, and our Code of Business Conduct and Ethics for Directors, which applies to our board of directors. The Codes of Business Conduct and Ethics are available on our website at
	www.investors.nimblestorage.com under &#147;Governance Documents.&#148; We intend to satisfy the disclosure requirement under Item&nbsp;5.05 of Form 8-K regarding amendment to, or waiver from, a provision of our Code of Business Conduct and Ethics
	by posting such information on our website at the address and location specified above.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	PART IV
</B>
</P>
<EFX_EXHIBITS>
<A NAME="FIS_EXHIBITS"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	IT
<A NAME="D139469D10K_HTM_TOC139469_20">
</A>
	EM&nbsp;15. EXHIBITS AND FINANCIAL STATEMENT SCHEDULES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	We have filed the following documents as a part of this Annual Report on Form 10-K:
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:5%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	(a) Financial Statements
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<EFX_EXHIBIT_10>
<A NAME="FIS_EXHIBIT_10"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<B>
	Exhibit 10.12
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	FIRST AMENDMENT TO CREDIT AGREEMENT
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	This First Amendment to Credit Agreement (this &#147;Amendment&#148;) is entered into as of April 23, 2014, by and between WELLS FARGO BANK,
	NATIONAL ASSOCIATION (&#147;Bank&#148;) and NIMBLE STORAGE, INC., a Delaware corporation (&#147;Borrower&#148;).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<U>
	RECITALS
</U>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Borrower and Bank are parties to that certain Credit Agreement dated as of October 1, 2013, as amended from time to time (the
	&#147;Agreement&#148;). The parties desire to amend the Agreement in accordance with the terms of this Amendment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	NOW, THEREFORE, the
	parties agree as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	1. Clause (viii) of the defined term, &#147;eligible accounts receivable&#148;, set forth in Section 1.1(b) of
	the Agreement hereby is amended and restated in its entirety to read as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&#147;(viii) except as otherwise approved by Bank in
	writing, that portion of any account from an account debtor which represents the amount by which Borrower&#146;s total accounts from said account debtor exceeds twenty-five percent (25%) of Borrower&#146;s total accounts; provided, however, with
	respect to accounts owing from Avnet, Inc., such percentage shall be fifty percent (50%);&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	2. Section 4.3(d) of the Agreement hereby
	is amended and restated in its entirety to read as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&#147;(d) not later than thirty (30) days after and as of the end of each
	month, a borrowing base certificate executed by the President, Chief Financial Officer or Controller of Borrower, an aged listing of accounts receivable and accounts payable, a reconciliation of accounts receivable and accounts payable, and a
	deferred revenue schedule, and immediately upon each request from Bank, a list of the names and addresses of all Borrower&#146;s account debtors;&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	3. Section 4.3(e) of the Agreement hereby is amended and restated in its entirety to read as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&#147;(e) contemporaneously with each annual and monthly financial statement of Borrower required hereby, a Compliance Certificate executed by
	the President, Chief Financial Officer or Controller of Borrower, including a certification that said financial statements are accurate and that there exists no Event of Default nor any condition, act or event which with the giving of notice or the
	passage of time or both would constitute an Event of Default;&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	4. Section 4.9(b) of the Agreement hereby is amended and restated in
	its entirety to read as follows :
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&#147;(b)
<U>
	EBITDA
</U>
	. EBITDA of not less than the covenant levels as set forth in the
	table immediately below for the following measuring periods, with &#147;EBITDA&#148; defined as net profit before tax plus interest expense (net of capitalized interest expense), depreciation expense, amortization expense and non-cash stock
	compensation expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	5. Section 5.2 of the Agreement hereby is amended and restated in its entirety to read as
	follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&#147;SECTION 5.2. CAPITAL EXPENDITURES. Make any additional investment in fixed assets in Borrower&#146;s 2014
	and 2015 fiscal years, combined, in excess of an aggregate of Forty Million Dollars ($40,000,000). Notwithstanding the foregoing, Borrower shall not make any additional investment in fixed assets in excess of an aggregate of Twenty Five Million
	Dollars ($25,000,000) in any one of Borrower&#146;s 2014 or 2015 fiscal years.&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	6. No course of dealing on the part of Bank or its
	officers, nor any failure or delay in the exercise of any right by Bank, shall operate as a waiver thereof, and any single or partial exercise of any such right shall not preclude any later exercise of any such right. Bank&#146;s failure at any time
	to require strict performance by Borrower of any provision shall not affect any right of Bank thereafter to demand strict compliance and performance. Any suspension or waiver of a right must be in writing signed by an officer of Bank.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	7. Unless otherwise defined, all initially capitalized terms in this Amendment shall be as defined in the Agreement. The Agreement, as amended
	hereby, shall be and remain in full force and effect in accordance with its respective terms and hereby is ratified and confirmed in all respects. Except as expressly set forth herein, the execution, delivery, and performance of this Amendment shall
	not operate as a waiver of, or as an amendment of, any right, power, or remedy of Bank under the Agreement, as in effect prior to the date hereof.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	8. Borrower represents and warrants that the Representations and Warranties contained in the Agreement are true and correct as of the date of
	this Amendment, and that no Event of Default has occurred and is continuing.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	9. As a condition to the effectiveness of this Amendment,
	Bank shall have received, in form and substance satisfactory to Bank:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	(a) this Amendment, duly executed by Borrower; and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	(b) all reasonable fees and expenses incurred through the date of this Amendment, which may be debited from Borrower&#146;s account at Bank.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	10. This Amendment may be executed in two or more counterparts, each of which shall be deemed an original, but all of which together
	shall constitute one instrument.
</P>

<EFX_EXHIBIT_10>
<A NAME="FIS_EXHIBIT_10_2"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<B>
	Exhibit 10.13
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	SECOND AMENDMENT TO CREDIT AGREEMENT
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	This Second Amendment to Credit Agreement (this &#147;Amendment&#148;) is entered into as of June 17, 2014, by and between WELLS FARGO BANK,
	NATIONAL ASSOCIATION (&#147;Bank&#148;) and NIMBLE STORAGE, INC., a Delaware corporation (&#147;Borrower&#148;).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<U>
	RECITALS
</U>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Borrower and Bank are parties to that certain Credit Agreement dated as of October 1, 2013 (as amended from time to time, including by that
	certain First Amendment to Loan and Security Agreement dated as of April 23, 2014, collectively, the &#147;Agreement&#148;). The parties desire to amend the Agreement in accordance with the terms of this Amendment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	NOW, THEREFORE, the parties agree as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	1. Section 1.1(c) of the Agreement hereby is amended and restated in its entirety to read as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&#147;(c)
<U>
	Letter of Credit Subfeature
</U>
	.&nbsp;As a subfeature under the Line of Credit, Bank agrees from time to time
	during the term thereof to issue or cause an affiliate to issue standby letters of credit for the account of Borrower (each, a &#147;Letter of Credit&#148; and collectively, &#147;Letters of Credit&#148;); provided however, that the aggregate
	undrawn amount of all outstanding Letters of Credit (the &#147;Letters of Credit Sublimit&#148;) shall not at any time exceed Eight Hundred Eighty Seven Thousand Ninety Nine Dollars $887,099.00). The form and substance of each Letter of Credit shall
	be subject to approval by Bank, in its sole discretion. Each Letter of Credit shall be issued for a term not to exceed three hundred sixty five (365) days, as designated by Borrower; provided however, if on the Line of Credit maturity date (or the
	effective date of any termination of this Agreement) there are any outstanding Letters of Credit, Borrower shall provide to Bank cash collateral in an amount equal to at least one hundred percent (100%) of the face amount of any such Letter of
	Credit, plus all interest, fees and costs due or to become due in connection therewith to secure the obligations related to such Letter of Credit. The undrawn amount of all Letters of Credit shall be reserved under the Line of Credit and shall not
	be available for borrowings thereunder. Each Letter of Credit shall be subject to the additional terms and conditions of the Letter of Credit agreements, applications and any related documents required by Bank in connection with the issuance
	thereof. Each drawing paid under a Letter of Credit shall be deemed an advance under the Line of Credit and shall be repaid by Borrower in accordance with the terms and conditions of this Agreement applicable to such advances; provided however, that
	if advances under the Line of Credit are not available, for any reason, at the time any drawing is paid, then Borrower shall immediately pay to Bank the full amount drawn, together with interest thereon from the date such drawing is paid to the date
	such amount is fully repaid by Borrower, at the rate of interest applicable to advances under the Line of Credit. In such event Borrower agrees that Bank, in its sole discretion, may debit any account maintained by Borrower with Bank for the amount
	of any such drawing.&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	2. New Section 1.1(d) hereby is added to the Agreement as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&#147;(d)
<U>
	Borrowing and Repayment
</U>
	. Borrower may from time to time during the term of the Line of Credit borrow, partially
	or wholly repay its outstanding borrowings, and reborrow, subject to all of the limitations, terms and conditions contained herein or in the Revolving Line of Credit Note; provided however, that the total outstanding borrowings under the Line of
	Credit shall not at any time exceed the maximum principal amount available thereunder, as set forth above. If, at any time, the outstanding borrowings under the Line of Credit exceed the maximum amount permitted under this Section 1.1, Borrower
	shall promptly pay to Bank in cash such excess.&#148;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage105"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	3. No course of dealing on the part of Bank or its officers, nor any failure or delay in the
	exercise of any right by Bank, shall operate as a waiver thereof, and any single or partial exercise of any such right shall not preclude any later exercise of any such right. Bank&#146;s failure at any time to require strict performance by Borrower
	of any provision shall not affect any right of Bank thereafter to demand strict compliance and performance. Any suspension or waiver of a right must be in writing signed by an officer of Bank.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	4. Unless otherwise defined, all initially capitalized terms in this Amendment shall be as defined in the Agreement. The Agreement, as amended
	hereby, shall be and remain in full force and effect in accordance with its respective terms and hereby is ratified and confirmed in all respects. Except as expressly set forth herein, the execution, delivery, and performance of this Amendment shall
	not operate as a waiver of, or as an amendment of, any right, power, or remedy of Bank under the Agreement, as in effect prior to the date hereof.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	5. Borrower represents and warrants that the Representations and Warranties contained in the Agreement are true and correct as of the date of
	this Amendment, and that no Event of Default has occurred and is continuing.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	6. As a condition to the effectiveness of this Amendment,
	Bank shall have received, in form and substance satisfactory to Bank:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	(a) this Amendment, duly executed by Borrower; and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	(b) all reasonable fees and expenses incurred through the date of this Amendment, which may be debited from Borrower&#146;s account at Bank.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	7. This Amendment may be executed in two or more counterparts, each of which shall be deemed an original, but all of which together shall
	constitute one instrument.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<I>
	[Balance of Page Intentionally Left Blank]
</I>
</B>

	IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the undersigned have executed this Amendment as of the first date above
	written.
</P>

<A NAME="eolPage107"></A>
<A NAME="D139469DEX1016_HTM"></A>
<EFX_EXHIBIT_10>
<A NAME="FIS_EXHIBIT_10_3"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<B>
	Exhibit 10.16
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	FIFTH AMENDMENT TO CREDIT AGREEMENT
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	This Fifth Amendment to Credit Agreement (this &#147;Amendment&#148;) is entered into as of December 9, 2015, by and between WELLS FARGO BANK,
	NATIONAL ASSOCIATION (&#147;Bank&#148;) and NIMBLE STORAGE, INC., a Delaware corporation (&#147;Borrower&#148;).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<U>
	RECITALS
</U>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Borrower and Bank are parties to that certain Credit Agreement dated as of October 1, 2013 (as amended from time to time, including by that
	certain First Amendment to Credit Agreement dated as of April 23, 2014, that certain Second Amendment to Credit Agreement dated as of June 17, 2014, that certain Third Amendment to Credit Agreement dated as of September 19, 2014 and that certain
	Fourth Amendment to Credit Agreement dated as of April 6, 2015, collectively, the &#147;Agreement&#148;). The parties desire to amend the Agreement in accordance with the terms of this Amendment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	NOW, THEREFORE, the parties agree as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	1. Section 1.1(c) of the Agreement hereby is amended and restated in its entirety to read as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&#147;(c)
<U>
	Letter of Credit Subfeature
</U>
	.&nbsp;As a subfeature under the Line of Credit, Bank agrees from time to time
	during the term thereof to issue or cause an affiliate to issue standby letters of credit for the account of Borrower (each, a &#147;Letter of Credit&#148; and collectively, &#147;Letters of Credit&#148;); provided however, that the aggregate
	undrawn amount of all outstanding Letters of Credit (the &#147;Letters of Credit Sublimit&#148;) shall not at any time exceed Seven Million Dollars ($7,000,000). The form and substance of each Letter of Credit shall be subject to approval by Bank,
	in its sole discretion. Each Letter of Credit shall be issued for a term not to exceed three hundred sixty five (365) days, as designated by Borrower; provided however, if on the Line of Credit maturity date (or the effective date of any termination
	of this Agreement) there are any outstanding Letters of Credit, Borrower shall provide to Bank cash collateral in an amount equal to at least one hundred percent (100%) of the face amount of any such Letter of Credit, plus all interest, fees and
	costs due or to become due in connection therewith to secure the obligations related to such Letter of Credit. The undrawn amount of all Letters of Credit shall be reserved under the Line of Credit and shall not be available for borrowings
	thereunder. Each Letter of Credit shall be subject to the additional terms and conditions of the Letter of Credit agreements, applications and any related documents required by Bank in connection with the issuance thereof. Each drawing paid under a
	Letter of Credit shall be deemed an advance under the Line of Credit and shall be repaid by Borrower in accordance with the terms and conditions of this Agreement applicable to such advances; provided however, that if advances under the Line of
	Credit are not available, for any reason, at the time any drawing is paid, then Borrower shall immediately pay to Bank the full amount drawn, together with interest thereon from the date such drawing is paid to the date such amount is fully repaid
	by Borrower, at the rate of interest applicable to advances under the Line of Credit. In such event Borrower agrees that Bank, in its sole discretion, may debit any account maintained by Borrower with Bank for the amount of any such drawing.&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	2. The Borrowing Base Certificate incorporated as part of the Loan Documents hereby is replaced with the Borrowing Base Certificate
	attached hereto.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	3. No course of dealing on the part of Bank or its officers, nor any failure or delay in the exercise of any right by
	Bank, shall operate as a waiver thereof, and any single or partial exercise of any such right shall not preclude any later exercise of any such right. Bank&#146;s failure at any time to require strict performance by Borrower of any provision shall
	not affect any right of Bank thereafter to demand strict compliance and performance.&nbsp;Any suspension or waiver of a right must be in writing signed by an officer of Bank.
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage108"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	4. Unless otherwise defined, all initially capitalized terms in this Amendment shall be as
	defined in the Agreement. The Agreement, as amended hereby, shall be and remain in full force and effect in accordance with its respective terms and hereby is ratified and confirmed in all respects. Except as expressly set forth herein, the
	execution, delivery, and performance of this Amendment shall not operate as a waiver of, or as an amendment of, any right, power, or remedy of Bank under the Agreement, as in effect prior to the date hereof.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	5. Borrower represents and warrants that the Representations and Warranties contained in the Agreement are true and correct as of the date of
	this Amendment, and that no Event of Default has occurred and is continuing.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	6. As a condition to the effectiveness of this Amendment,
	Bank shall have received, in form and substance satisfactory to Bank:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	(a) this Amendment, duly executed by Borrower; and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	(b) all reasonable fees and expenses incurred through the date of this Amendment, which may be debited from Borrower&#146;s account at Bank.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	7. This Amendment may be executed in two or more counterparts, each of which shall be deemed an original, but all of which together shall
	constitute one instrument.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<I>
	[Balance of Page Intentionally Left Blank]
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	2
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the undersigned have executed this Amendment as of the first date above
	written.
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

	&nbsp;

	statements were made, not misleading with respect to the period covered by this report;

</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;

	registrant as of, and for, the periods presented in this report;

	registrant&#146;s board of directors (or persons performing the equivalent functions):

	process, summarize and report financial information; and

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

	statements were made, not misleading with respect to the period covered by this report;

</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

</TD>

	registrant as of, and for, the periods presented in this report;

</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;

	over financial reporting (as defined in E xchange Act Rules 13a-15(f) and 15d-15(f)) for the registrant and have:

	consolidated subsidiaries, is made known to us by others within those entities, particularly during the period in which this report is being prepared;
</TD>
